1
00:00:04,046 --> 00:00:05,923
(GRUNTING)

2
00:02:25,562 --> 00:02:27,689
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

3
00:03:08,772 --> 00:03:10,399
Kathy?

4
00:03:10,482 --> 00:03:13,276
DOCTOR: Listen, your life
could depend on this.

5
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:17,656
Don't blink. Don't even blink.
Blink and you're dead.

6
00:03:18,532 --> 00:03:20,992
They are fast.
Faster than you can believe.

7
00:03:21,118 --> 00:03:25,664
Don't turn your back,
don't look away and don't blink.

8
00:03:27,290 --> 00:03:28,875
Good luck.

9
00:03:41,096 --> 00:03:42,973
(MOBILE RINGING)

10
00:03:50,814 --> 00:03:51,940
Hello?

11
00:03:52,023 --> 00:03:55,110
Bit freaked. Need to talk.
Making you a coffee.

12
00:03:55,193 --> 00:03:58,321
Sally Sparrow, it's 1:00 in the morning.

13
00:03:58,447 --> 00:04:00,866
Do you think I'm going out
at 1:00 in the morning?

14
00:04:00,991 --> 00:04:02,159
No.

15
00:04:02,284 --> 00:04:06,204
I'm in the kitchen. What's that
on all those screens in your front room?

16
00:04:06,329 --> 00:04:07,664
(SIGHING) Oh, God.

17
00:04:07,748 --> 00:04:09,249
(TOILET FLUSHING)

18
00:04:09,332 --> 00:04:12,753
Oh, God. Sally, you've met
my brother Larry, haven't you?

19
00:04:12,836 --> 00:04:14,421
-No.
-You're about to.

20
00:04:14,504 --> 00:04:15,964
(DOOR OPENING)

21
00:04:16,631 --> 00:04:18,592
Okay.

22
00:04:18,675 --> 00:04:24,181
Not sure, but really, really hoping...

23
00:04:25,849 --> 00:04:28,143
-Pants?
-No.

24
00:04:31,855 --> 00:04:36,234
Put them on! Put them on! I hate you!

25
00:04:36,818 --> 00:04:39,070
What are you thinking?

26
00:04:40,697 --> 00:04:44,284
Sorry. My useless brother.

27
00:04:46,036 --> 00:04:48,497
Sally? What's wrong?

28
00:04:50,373 --> 00:04:52,042
What's happened?

29
00:04:55,962 --> 00:05:01,885
Okay. Let's investigate.
You and me, girl investigators.

30
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:05,806
Love it. Hey! Sparrow and Nightingale.

31
00:05:05,889 --> 00:05:08,225
-That so works.
-Bit ITV.

32
00:05:08,350 --> 00:05:10,268
I know!

33
00:05:13,688 --> 00:05:16,149
What did you come here for anyway?

34
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:20,320
I love old things.
They make me feel sad.

35
00:05:21,738 --> 00:05:27,786
-What's good about sad?
-It's happy for deep people.

36
00:05:43,552 --> 00:05:45,679
The weeping angel.

37
00:05:45,762 --> 00:05:47,806
KATHY: Wouldn't have that in my garden.

38
00:05:48,682 --> 00:05:51,768
-It's moved.
-It's what?

39
00:05:52,269 --> 00:05:56,398
Since yesterday.
I'm sure of it. It's closer.

40
00:05:56,815 --> 00:05:59,150
It's got closer to the house.

41
00:06:09,286 --> 00:06:11,329
How can my name be written here?

42
00:06:14,165 --> 00:06:16,084
How is that possible?

43
00:06:16,251 --> 00:06:18,253
(DOORBELL RINGING)

44
00:06:20,338 --> 00:06:22,257
Who'd come here?

45
00:06:23,842 --> 00:06:25,719
-What are you doing?
-It could be a burglar.

46
00:06:25,802 --> 00:06:27,929
A burglar who rings the doorbell?

47
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:33,310
-Okay. I'll stay here in case of...
-In case of?

48
00:06:34,060 --> 00:06:36,146
-Incidents?
-Okay.

49
00:06:49,367 --> 00:06:52,537
I'm looking for Sally Sparrow.

50
00:06:53,246 --> 00:06:55,457
How did you know I'd be here?

51
00:06:55,540 --> 00:07:01,796
I was told to bring this letter
on this date at this exact time

52
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:03,673
to Sally Sparrow.

53
00:07:05,133 --> 00:07:07,761
-Looks old.
-It is old.

54
00:07:08,345 --> 00:07:11,348
I'm sorry, do you have anything
with a photograph on it,

55
00:07:11,431 --> 00:07:13,350
like a driving licence?

56
00:07:15,226 --> 00:07:16,645
(RATTLING)

57
00:07:16,728 --> 00:07:19,439
No one knew I was coming here.
I didn't tell anyone.

58
00:07:19,522 --> 00:07:21,107
How could anyone have known?

59
00:07:21,191 --> 00:07:25,695
MAN: It's all a bit complicated.
I'm not sure I understand it myself.

60
00:07:36,915 --> 00:07:42,879
Yes. Sorry, I feel really stupid.
I was told to make absolutely sure.

61
00:07:43,004 --> 00:07:45,632
It's so hard to tell
with these little photographs, isn't it?

62
00:07:45,715 --> 00:07:47,175
Apparently.

63
00:07:51,388 --> 00:07:54,808
Well, here goes, I suppose.

64
00:07:56,768 --> 00:08:00,230
-Funny feeling after all these years.
-Who's it from?

65
00:08:00,313 --> 00:08:04,567
-Well, that's a long story, actually.
-Give me a name.

66
00:08:06,069 --> 00:08:08,488
Katherine Wainwright.

67
00:08:08,571 --> 00:08:12,242
But she specified I should tell you
that, prior to marriage,

68
00:08:12,701 --> 00:08:16,162
she was called Kathy Nightingale.

69
00:08:16,371 --> 00:08:17,914
(BANGING)

70
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:20,166
Kathy?

71
00:08:21,209 --> 00:08:23,628
Kathy. Yes.

72
00:08:25,130 --> 00:08:27,841
Katherine Costello Nightingale.

73
00:08:27,924 --> 00:08:30,468
-Is this a joke?
-Joke?

74
00:08:31,803 --> 00:08:34,055
Kathy, is this you?

75
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:37,267
Very funny. Kathy?

76
00:08:48,945 --> 00:08:52,198
-Kathy? Kathy?
-Please.

77
00:08:52,824 --> 00:08:56,327
You need to take this. I promised.

78
00:08:59,539 --> 00:09:03,460
Excuse me. Where am I?

79
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:07,130
I was in London.
I was in the middle of London.

80
00:09:07,213 --> 00:09:10,008
-You're in Hull.
-No, I'm not.

81
00:09:10,258 --> 00:09:12,677
-This is Hull.
-No, it isn't.

82
00:09:12,844 --> 00:09:16,890
-You're in Hull.
-I'm not in Hull. Stop saying Hull.

83
00:09:17,140 --> 00:09:20,226
Who are you? Why are you here?

84
00:09:20,310 --> 00:09:22,854
-I made a promise.
-Who to?

85
00:09:22,979 --> 00:09:26,483
My grandmother.
Katherine Costello Nightingale.

86
00:09:27,984 --> 00:09:31,529
Don't have that in London.
There's no call for it. It's all Hull.

87
00:09:33,698 --> 00:09:35,533
19207

88
00:09:38,536 --> 00:09:40,413
-Your grandmother?
-Yes.

89
00:09:40,497 --> 00:09:42,582
She died 20 years ago.

90
00:09:42,999 --> 00:09:44,209
Huh.

91
00:09:50,715 --> 00:09:53,551
-So they're related?
-Sorry?

92
00:09:53,635 --> 00:09:56,638
My Kathy, your grandmother.
They're practically identical.

93
00:09:59,724 --> 00:10:01,559
Where you going?

94
00:10:05,021 --> 00:10:07,816
My dearest Sally Sparrow,

95
00:10:07,899 --> 00:10:10,401
if my grandson has done
as he promises he will,

96
00:10:10,485 --> 00:10:12,070
then as you read these words,

97
00:10:12,153 --> 00:10:15,115
it has been mere minutes
since we last spoke.

98
00:10:15,198 --> 00:10:19,494
For you. For me,
it has been over 60 years.

99
00:10:20,286 --> 00:10:23,373
The third of the photographs
is of my children.

100
00:10:23,456 --> 00:10:27,961
The youngest is Sally.
I named her after you, of course.

101
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:33,383
This is sick.

102
00:10:35,218 --> 00:10:37,887
This is totally sick.

103
00:10:38,304 --> 00:10:41,266
Kathy? Kathy!

104
00:10:42,976 --> 00:10:44,352
Kathy?

105
00:11:00,827 --> 00:11:02,412
(FLUTTERING)

106
00:11:49,459 --> 00:11:50,543
(DOOR CLOSING)

107
00:11:50,627 --> 00:11:52,879
No, wait. Hang on!

108
00:12:25,328 --> 00:12:29,832
I suppose, unless I live
to a really exceptional old age,

109
00:12:29,916 --> 00:12:33,002
I will be long gone as you read this.

110
00:12:33,336 --> 00:12:37,799
Don't feel sorry for me.
I have led a good and full life.

111
00:12:38,132 --> 00:12:42,220
I've loved a good man
and been well loved in return.

112
00:12:43,930 --> 00:12:45,932
You would have liked Ben.

113
00:12:46,015 --> 00:12:49,686
He was the very first person I met
in 71920.

114
00:12:50,645 --> 00:12:52,855
-Are you following me?
-Yeah.

115
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:58,611
-Are you going to stop following me?
-No, I don't think so.

116
00:13:01,322 --> 00:13:05,618
To take one breath in 2007
and the next in 1920

117
00:13:05,702 --> 00:13:08,621
Is a strange way to start a new life,

118
00:13:08,705 --> 00:13:12,333
but a new life
is exactly what I've always wanted.

119
00:13:12,458 --> 00:13:14,377
1902.

120
00:13:16,421 --> 00:13:19,674
You told him you were 18, you lying cow.

121
00:13:21,259 --> 00:13:26,306
My mum and dad are gone by your time,
so really there's only Lawrence to tell.

122
00:13:26,514 --> 00:13:29,809
He works at the DVD store
on Queen Street.

123
00:13:30,393 --> 00:13:32,395
I don't know
what you're gonna say to him,

124
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:35,064
but I know you'll think of something.

125
00:13:36,733 --> 00:13:38,901
Just tell him I love him.

126
00:13:55,585 --> 00:13:58,588
Excuse me,
I'm looking for Lawrence Nightingale.

127
00:13:59,213 --> 00:14:00,715
In the back.

128
00:14:11,059 --> 00:14:12,393
Hello?

129
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:19,942
-Martha!
-Sorry.

130
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:23,988
Quite possibly.

131
00:14:25,990 --> 00:14:27,367
Afraid so.

132
00:14:28,618 --> 00:14:31,120
Oh. Hello.

133
00:14:31,412 --> 00:14:32,997
-Can I help you?
-Hi.

134
00:14:33,122 --> 00:14:34,624
38.

135
00:14:35,708 --> 00:14:37,543
Just a moment.

136
00:14:43,883 --> 00:14:46,552
Hang on. We've met, haven't we?

137
00:14:47,178 --> 00:14:48,971
It'll come to you.

138
00:14:50,014 --> 00:14:52,517
-Oh, my God.
-There it is.

139
00:14:52,642 --> 00:14:55,478
Sorry. Sorry, again, about the whole...

140
00:14:55,603 --> 00:14:59,148
-Message from your sister.
-Oh, okay.

141
00:15:01,484 --> 00:15:04,654
What? What is it? What's the message?

142
00:15:05,196 --> 00:15:07,907
-She's had to go away for a bit.
-Where?

143
00:15:07,990 --> 00:15:10,451
Just a work thing.
Nothing to worry about.

144
00:15:10,535 --> 00:15:13,329
-Okay.
-And...

145
00:15:14,288 --> 00:15:17,166
-And... And what?
-She loves you.

146
00:15:17,792 --> 00:15:19,085
She what?

147
00:15:19,168 --> 00:15:22,130
She said to say...
She just sort of mentioned it.

148
00:15:22,213 --> 00:15:24,841
She loves you.
There, that's nice, isn't it?

149
00:15:26,300 --> 00:15:28,302
-Is she ill?
-No! No.

150
00:15:28,386 --> 00:15:30,513
-Am I ill?
-No.

151
00:15:31,180 --> 00:15:34,517
-Is this a trick?
-No. She loves you.

152
00:15:34,892 --> 00:15:39,230
People don't understand time.
It's not what you think it is.

153
00:15:39,897 --> 00:15:43,151
-Who is this guy?
-Sorry, the pause thing keeps slipping.

154
00:15:43,234 --> 00:15:45,194
-Stupid thing.
-Last night at Kathy's,

155
00:15:45,278 --> 00:15:47,488
you had him on all those screens,
that same guy.

156
00:15:47,572 --> 00:15:50,241
Talking about, I don't know,
blinking or something.

157
00:15:50,366 --> 00:15:52,118
Yeah, the bit
about the blinking's great.

158
00:15:52,243 --> 00:15:54,120
I was just checking to see
if they were all the same.

159
00:15:54,203 --> 00:15:55,788
What were the same?

160
00:15:55,872 --> 00:15:58,708
-What is this? Who is he?
-An Easter egg.

161
00:15:59,750 --> 00:16:02,295
-Excuse me?
-Like a DVD extra, yeah?

162
00:16:02,378 --> 00:16:05,631
You know how on DVDs they put extras,
you know, documentaries and stuff?

163
00:16:05,715 --> 00:16:08,885
Sometimes they put on hidden ones
and they call them Easter eggs.

164
00:16:09,010 --> 00:16:10,636
You have to go looking for them,

165
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:12,763
follow a bunch of clues
on the menu screen.

166
00:16:12,847 --> 00:16:14,474
Complicated.

167
00:16:14,557 --> 00:16:16,100
Sorry.

168
00:16:16,642 --> 00:16:21,147
It's interesting, actually.
He is on 17 different DVDs.

169
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:24,775
There are 17 totally unrelated DVDs
all with him on,

170
00:16:24,901 --> 00:16:28,279
always hidden away, always a secret.
Not even the publishers know.

171
00:16:28,362 --> 00:16:32,658
I've talked to the manufacturers, right?
They don't even know.

172
00:16:32,742 --> 00:16:35,119
He's like... He's a ghost DVD extra.

173
00:16:35,244 --> 00:16:36,871
Just shows up
where he's not supposed to be.

174
00:16:36,954 --> 00:16:41,083
-But only on those. Those 17.
-Well, what does he do?

175
00:16:41,250 --> 00:16:43,461
Just sits there, making random remarks.

176
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:46,047
It's like we're hearing
half a conversation.

177
00:16:46,130 --> 00:16:49,509
Me and the guys are always trying
to work out the other half.

178
00:16:49,592 --> 00:16:53,137
When you say you and the guys,
you mean the internet, don't you?

179
00:16:53,930 --> 00:16:56,265
-How'd you know?
-Spooky, isn't it?

180
00:16:57,725 --> 00:16:59,810
Very complicated.

181
00:16:59,936 --> 00:17:03,439
-Lawrence, need you.
-Excuse me a sec.

182
00:17:05,358 --> 00:17:09,028
People assume that time is
a strict progression of cause to effect,

183
00:17:09,111 --> 00:17:12,198
but actually, from a non-linear,
non-subjective viewpoint,

184
00:17:12,281 --> 00:17:17,703
it's more like a big ball
of wibbly-wobbly, timey-wimey stuff.

185
00:17:17,954 --> 00:17:19,956
It started well, that sentence.

186
00:17:20,331 --> 00:17:22,458
It got away from me, yeah.

187
00:17:23,167 --> 00:17:25,503
Okay, that was weird.
Like you can hear me.

188
00:17:25,628 --> 00:17:27,088
Well I can hear you.

189
00:17:27,171 --> 00:17:28,839
Okay, that's enough.

190
00:17:28,965 --> 00:17:32,843
I've had enough now. I've had a long day
and I've had bloody enough.

191
00:17:32,969 --> 00:17:36,138
Sorry, bad day.

192
00:17:37,807 --> 00:17:40,726
-Got you the list.
-What?

193
00:17:40,977 --> 00:17:44,313
The 17 DVDs.
I thought you might be interested.

194
00:17:44,939 --> 00:17:47,817
Yeah. Great. Thanks.

195
00:17:50,111 --> 00:17:53,072
Go to the police, you stupid woman.

196
00:17:53,155 --> 00:17:56,117
Why does nobody ever just go
to the police?

197
00:18:07,545 --> 00:18:09,922
Look, I know how mad I'm sounding.

198
00:18:10,006 --> 00:18:12,049
Shall we try it from the beginning
this time?

199
00:18:12,174 --> 00:18:15,469
Okay, there's this house,
a big, old house, been empty for years,

200
00:18:15,553 --> 00:18:18,347
falling apart, Wester Drumlins,
out by the estate.

201
00:18:18,431 --> 00:18:20,182
You've probably seen it.

202
00:18:20,266 --> 00:18:23,102
-Wester Drumlins?
-Yes.

203
00:18:23,185 --> 00:18:25,855
-Could you just wait here for a minute?
-Oh.

204
00:18:57,053 --> 00:19:00,264
Okay. Cracking up now.

205
00:19:02,558 --> 00:19:06,479
Hi. DI Billy Shipton.
Wester Drumlins, that's mine.

206
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:08,856
Can't talk to you now,
got a thing I can't be late for,

207
00:19:08,939 --> 00:19:10,900
so if you could just...

208
00:19:12,401 --> 00:19:15,029
-Hello.
-Hello.

209
00:19:16,405 --> 00:19:21,077
Er, Marcie, can you tell them
I'm going to be late for that thing?

210
00:19:26,207 --> 00:19:29,543
-All of them?
-Over the last two years, yeah.

211
00:19:29,627 --> 00:19:31,712
They all still have personal items
in them

212
00:19:31,796 --> 00:19:34,382
and a couple still had
the motor running.

213
00:19:34,465 --> 00:19:36,092
So over the last two years,

214
00:19:36,175 --> 00:19:38,386
the owners of all of these vehicles
have driven up

215
00:19:38,469 --> 00:19:43,057
to Wester Drumlins house,
parked outside and just disappeared?

216
00:19:46,268 --> 00:19:48,896
-What's that?
-Ah.

217
00:19:48,979 --> 00:19:51,607
The pride of
the Wester Drumlins collection.

218
00:19:51,691 --> 00:19:55,945
We found that there, too.
Somebody's idea of a joke, I suppose.

219
00:19:56,445 --> 00:19:58,447
But what is it? What's a police box?

220
00:19:58,572 --> 00:20:01,200
Well, it's a special kind of phone box
for policemen.

221
00:20:01,283 --> 00:20:04,328
They used to have them all over,
but this isn't a real one.

222
00:20:04,453 --> 00:20:07,665
The phone is just a dummy
and the windows are the wrong size.

223
00:20:07,790 --> 00:20:09,375
Can't even get in it.

224
00:20:09,458 --> 00:20:12,211
Ordinary Yale lock, but nothing fits.

225
00:20:12,628 --> 00:20:15,131
But that's not the big question.

226
00:20:15,214 --> 00:20:18,509
See, you're missing the big question.

227
00:20:18,718 --> 00:20:21,178
Okay, what's the big question?

228
00:20:21,262 --> 00:20:24,974
-Will you have a drink with me?
-I'm sorry?

229
00:20:25,433 --> 00:20:28,310
Drink? You, me, now?

230
00:20:28,602 --> 00:20:32,148
Aren't you on duty,
Detective Inspector Shipton?

231
00:20:32,231 --> 00:20:34,608
Nope. Knocked off before I left.

232
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:37,361
-Told them I had a family crisis.
-Why?

233
00:20:37,445 --> 00:20:40,698
Because life is short
and you are hot. Drink?

234
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:42,783
No.

235
00:20:42,867 --> 00:20:45,035
-Ever?
-Maybe.

236
00:20:45,453 --> 00:20:48,247
-Phone number?
-Moving rather fast, DI Shipton.

237
00:20:48,330 --> 00:20:51,625
-Billy. I'm off duty.
-Aren't you just?

238
00:20:53,961 --> 00:20:56,547
-Is that your phone number?
-Just my phone number.

239
00:20:56,714 --> 00:21:02,845
Not a promise, not a guarantee,
not an IOU, just a phone number.

240
00:21:03,179 --> 00:21:05,306
-And that's Sally...
-Sally Shipton.

241
00:21:05,389 --> 00:21:07,767
Sparrow! Sally Sparrow.

242
00:21:08,642 --> 00:21:11,729
-Ah.
-Okay, going now. Don't look at me.

243
00:21:11,812 --> 00:21:13,272
-I'll phone you.
-Don't look at me.

244
00:21:13,355 --> 00:21:14,648
-Phone you tomorrow.
-Don't look at me.

245
00:21:14,732 --> 00:21:16,942
-Might even phone you tonight.
-Don't look at me.

246
00:21:17,026 --> 00:21:19,111
Definitely gonna phone you,
gorgeous girl.

247
00:21:19,195 --> 00:21:21,405
Definitely better.

248
00:22:36,522 --> 00:22:39,358
SHIPTON: Ordinary Yale lock,
but nothing fits.

249
00:23:04,592 --> 00:23:06,385
DOCTOR: Welcome.

250
00:23:07,052 --> 00:23:09,638
-Where am I?
-1969.

251
00:23:09,805 --> 00:23:12,099
Not bad, as it goes. You've got
the moon landing to look forward to.

252
00:23:12,182 --> 00:23:15,144
Oh, the moon landing's brilliant!
We went four times.

253
00:23:15,227 --> 00:23:17,897
-Back when we had transport.
-Working on it.

254
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:20,065
-How did I get here?
-Same way we did.

255
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:23,277
Touch of an angel. Same one, probably,
since you ended up in the same year.

256
00:23:23,360 --> 00:23:27,114
No, no, no. Don't get up.
Time travel without a capsule, nasty.

257
00:23:27,197 --> 00:23:29,617
Catch your breath,
don't go swimming for half an hour.

258
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:31,327
I don't... I can't...

259
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:33,913
Fascinating race, the weeping angels.

260
00:23:33,996 --> 00:23:36,790
The only psychopaths in the universe
to kill you nicely.

261
00:23:36,874 --> 00:23:40,586
No mess, no fuss, they just zap you
into the past and let you live to death,

262
00:23:40,669 --> 00:23:44,673
the rest of your life used up
and blown away in the blink of an eye.

263
00:23:44,840 --> 00:23:46,342
You die in the past and in the present

264
00:23:46,467 --> 00:23:49,345
they consume the energy
of all the days you might have had.

265
00:23:49,428 --> 00:23:51,972
All your stolen moments.

266
00:23:52,056 --> 00:23:55,726
They're creatures of the abstract,
they live off potential energy.

267
00:23:55,809 --> 00:23:57,561
What in God's name
are you talking about?

268
00:23:57,645 --> 00:24:00,356
Trust me, just nod
when he stops for breath.

269
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:04,693
Tracked you down with this.
This is my timey-wimey detector.

270
00:24:05,611 --> 00:24:09,823
Goes "bing" when there's stuff.
Also, it can boil an egg at 30 paces.

271
00:24:09,907 --> 00:24:13,577
Whether you want it to or not, actually,
so I've learnt to stay away from hens.

272
00:24:13,661 --> 00:24:15,955
It's not pretty when they blow.

273
00:24:16,747 --> 00:24:20,459
-I don't understand. Where am I?
-1969, like he said.

274
00:24:20,542 --> 00:24:24,755
Normally, I'd offer you a lift home,
but somebody nicked my motor.

275
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:28,509
So I need you to take
a message to Sally Sparrow.

276
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:34,098
And I'm sorry, Billy,
I am very, very sorry.

277
00:24:35,057 --> 00:24:38,143
It's gonna take you a while.

278
00:24:38,394 --> 00:24:40,229
(MOBILE RINGING)

279
00:24:40,729 --> 00:24:42,106
Hello?

280
00:24:42,564 --> 00:24:45,067
Billy, where are you?

281
00:24:46,068 --> 00:24:47,319
Where?

282
00:25:04,962 --> 00:25:06,213
Billy?

283
00:25:24,523 --> 00:25:26,608
It was raining when we met.

284
00:25:29,278 --> 00:25:31,155
It's the same rain.

285
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:46,462
-She looks nice.
-Her name was Sally, too.

286
00:25:46,962 --> 00:25:50,340
-Sally Shipton.
-Sally Shipton.

287
00:25:54,803 --> 00:25:58,182
I often thought about looking for you
before tonight.

288
00:25:58,265 --> 00:26:02,311
But apparently it would have torn
a hole in the fabric of space and time

289
00:26:02,478 --> 00:26:05,481
and destroyed
two thirds of the universe.

290
00:26:06,065 --> 00:26:09,401
Also, I'd lost my hair.

291
00:26:11,445 --> 00:26:13,530
Two thirds of the universe?
Where'd you get that from?

292
00:26:13,614 --> 00:26:17,826
There's a man in 1969.
He sent me with a message for you.

293
00:26:18,035 --> 00:26:20,496
-What man?
-The Doctor.

294
00:26:21,705 --> 00:26:24,708
-And what was the message?
-Just this,

295
00:26:24,833 --> 00:26:27,461
-look at the list.
-What does that mean?

296
00:26:27,544 --> 00:26:30,756
-Is that it? Look at the list?
-He said you'd have it by now.

297
00:26:30,839 --> 00:26:33,175
A list of 17 DVDs.

298
00:26:39,515 --> 00:26:41,600
I didn't stay a policeman back then.

299
00:26:41,683 --> 00:26:45,521
Got into publishing,
then video publishing.

300
00:26:45,896 --> 00:26:48,440
Then DVDs, of course.

301
00:26:50,025 --> 00:26:52,319
You put the Easter egg on.

302
00:26:54,696 --> 00:26:58,408
Have you noticed
what all 17 DVDs have in common yet?

303
00:26:59,201 --> 00:27:02,287
I suppose it's hard for you in a way.

304
00:27:02,871 --> 00:27:05,290
How could the Doctor have even known
I had a list?

305
00:27:05,374 --> 00:27:07,501
-I only just got this.
-I asked him how,

306
00:27:07,626 --> 00:27:10,963
but he said he couldn't tell me.

307
00:27:11,046 --> 00:27:16,885
He said you'd understand it one day,
but that I never would.

308
00:27:17,511 --> 00:27:20,430
Soon as I understand it,
I'll come and tell you.

309
00:27:21,056 --> 00:27:24,059
No, gorgeous girl. You can't.

310
00:27:24,852 --> 00:27:26,603
There's only tonight.

311
00:27:26,728 --> 00:27:30,607
He told me all those years ago,
that we'll only meet again

312
00:27:30,732 --> 00:27:32,234
this one time.

313
00:27:32,985 --> 00:27:34,736
On the night I die.

314
00:27:36,196 --> 00:27:37,823
Oh, Billy.

315
00:27:37,906 --> 00:27:42,202
It's kept me going.
I'm an old, sick man.

316
00:27:42,286 --> 00:27:45,455
But I've had
something to look forward to.

317
00:27:49,585 --> 00:27:54,423
Ah, life is long and you are hot.

318
00:27:59,094 --> 00:28:01,096
Look at my hands.

319
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:04,266
An old man's hands.

320
00:28:05,100 --> 00:28:07,311
How did that happen?

321
00:28:09,771 --> 00:28:13,984
I'll stay.
I'm gonna stay with you, okay?

322
00:28:15,068 --> 00:28:17,070
Thank you, Sally Sparrow.

323
00:28:20,115 --> 00:28:22,326
I have till the rain stops.

324
00:28:55,484 --> 00:28:56,818
(MOBILE RINGING)

325
00:28:57,194 --> 00:28:58,779
-Bantos.
-SALLY: They're mine.

326
00:28:58,862 --> 00:28:59,947
What?

327
00:29:00,072 --> 00:29:04,159
The DVDs on the list, the 17 DVDs,
what they've got in common is me.

328
00:29:04,243 --> 00:29:08,038
They're all the DVDs I own.
The Easter egg was intended for me.

329
00:29:08,497 --> 00:29:13,085
-You've only got 17 DVDs?
-Do you have a portable DVD player?

330
00:29:13,168 --> 00:29:15,212
-Of course. Why?
-I want you to meet me.

331
00:29:15,337 --> 00:29:16,630
Where?

332
00:29:16,713 --> 00:29:18,507
Wester Drumlins.

333
00:29:20,717 --> 00:29:23,178
I knew you would live
in Scooby Doo's house.

334
00:29:24,346 --> 00:29:27,015
For God's sake, I don't live here.

335
00:29:28,850 --> 00:29:31,520
Okay. This is the one
with the clearest sound.

336
00:29:31,603 --> 00:29:33,438
Slightly better picture quality
on this one,

337
00:29:33,522 --> 00:29:35,649
-but I don't know...
-Doesn't matter.

338
00:29:35,732 --> 00:29:37,025
Okay.

339
00:29:45,617 --> 00:29:47,577
There he is.

340
00:29:53,125 --> 00:29:55,752
-The Doctor.
-Who's a doctor?

341
00:29:55,877 --> 00:29:58,547
-He's the Doctor.
-Yup, that's me.

342
00:29:58,797 --> 00:30:01,425
-Okay, that was scary.
-No, it sounds like he's replying,

343
00:30:01,550 --> 00:30:03,468
-but he always says that.
-Yes, I do.

344
00:30:03,593 --> 00:30:06,471
-And that.
-Yup. And this.

345
00:30:06,555 --> 00:30:08,307
He can hear us.

346
00:30:08,432 --> 00:30:11,435
-Oh, my God. You can really hear us.
-Of course he can't hear us.

347
00:30:11,560 --> 00:30:12,894
Look.

348
00:30:14,521 --> 00:30:17,274
I've got a transcript, see?
Everything he says.

349
00:30:17,399 --> 00:30:20,569
"Yup, that's me." "Yes, I do."”
"Yup, and this." Next, it's...

350
00:30:20,652 --> 00:30:22,988
BOTH: Are you gonna read
out the whole thing?

351
00:30:23,113 --> 00:30:24,156
Sorry.

352
00:30:24,239 --> 00:30:25,657
Who are you?

353
00:30:25,741 --> 00:30:30,996
I'm a time traveller. Or I was.
I'm stuck in 1969.

354
00:30:31,413 --> 00:30:34,041
We're stuck. All of space and time,
he promised me.

355
00:30:34,124 --> 00:30:36,335
Now I've got a job in a shop.
I've gotta support him!

356
00:30:36,418 --> 00:30:38,045
-Martha!
-Sorry.

357
00:30:38,337 --> 00:30:40,047
I've seen this bit before.

358
00:30:40,130 --> 00:30:41,840
Quite possibly.

359
00:30:42,257 --> 00:30:46,261
-1969, that's where you're talking from?
-Afraid so.

360
00:30:47,054 --> 00:30:49,139
But you're replying to me.

361
00:30:49,222 --> 00:30:52,601
You can't know exactly what
I'm gonna say 40 years before I say it.

362
00:30:52,684 --> 00:30:53,727
38.

363
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:55,937
I'm getting this down.
I'm writing in your bits.

364
00:30:56,063 --> 00:30:59,649
-How? How is this possible? Tell me.
-Not so fast.

365
00:30:59,900 --> 00:31:03,528
People don't understand time.
It's not what you think it is.

366
00:31:03,612 --> 00:31:04,905
Then what is it?

367
00:31:04,988 --> 00:31:07,240
-Complicated.
-Tell me.

368
00:31:07,491 --> 00:31:10,952
-Very complicated.
-I'm clever and I'm listening.

369
00:31:11,036 --> 00:31:13,121
And don't patronise me
because people have died

370
00:31:13,246 --> 00:31:15,791
and I'm not happy. Tell me.

371
00:31:17,417 --> 00:31:21,046
People assume that time is
a strict progression of cause to effect,

372
00:31:21,129 --> 00:31:23,924
but actually, from a non-linear,
non-subjective viewpoint,

373
00:31:24,007 --> 00:31:29,304
it's more like a big ball
of wibbly-wobbly, timey-wimey stuff.

374
00:31:29,429 --> 00:31:30,806
Yeah, I've seen this bit before.

375
00:31:30,889 --> 00:31:32,766
You said that sentence got away
from you.

376
00:31:32,849 --> 00:31:34,601
It got away from me, yeah.

377
00:31:34,684 --> 00:31:37,813
Next thing you're gonna say is,
"Well, I can hear you."

378
00:31:37,896 --> 00:31:39,147
Well I can hear you.

379
00:31:39,231 --> 00:31:42,150
-This is impossible.
-No. It's brilliant!

380
00:31:42,234 --> 00:31:45,862
Well, not hear you, exactly,
but I know everything you're gonna say.

381
00:31:45,987 --> 00:31:48,115
Always gives me the shivers, that bit.

382
00:31:48,198 --> 00:31:50,826
How can you know what I'm gonna say?

383
00:31:50,909 --> 00:31:53,995
-Look to your left.
-What's he mean by "look to your left"?

384
00:31:54,121 --> 00:31:55,747
I've written tons about that
in the forums.

385
00:31:55,831 --> 00:31:57,916
I think it's a political statement.

386
00:31:57,999 --> 00:32:00,669
He means you. What are you doing?

387
00:32:01,711 --> 00:32:03,130
I'm writing in your bits.

388
00:32:03,213 --> 00:32:06,383
That way, I've got a complete transcript
of the whole conversation.

389
00:32:06,550 --> 00:32:10,720
Wait until this hits the Net.
This will explode the egg forums.

390
00:32:11,847 --> 00:32:14,516
I've got a copy of the finished
transcript, it's on my Autocue.

391
00:32:14,599 --> 00:32:16,226
How can you have
a copy of the finished transcript?

392
00:32:16,351 --> 00:32:17,853
It's still being written.

393
00:32:17,978 --> 00:32:20,522
I told you, I'm a time traveller.
I got it in the future.

394
00:32:20,605 --> 00:32:22,482
Okay, let me get my head round this.

395
00:32:22,566 --> 00:32:26,445
You're reading aloud from a transcript
of a conversation you're still having.

396
00:32:26,528 --> 00:32:29,364
Wibbly-wobbly, timey-wimey...

397
00:32:29,448 --> 00:32:32,534
Actually, never mind that.
You can do shorthand?

398
00:32:33,660 --> 00:32:35,078
So?

399
00:32:35,162 --> 00:32:38,832
What matters is we can communicate.
We have got big problems now.

400
00:32:38,999 --> 00:32:41,209
They have taken the blue box,
haven't they?

401
00:32:41,334 --> 00:32:43,128
The angels have the phone box?

402
00:32:43,295 --> 00:32:45,547
"The angels have the phone box",
that's my favourite.

403
00:32:45,672 --> 00:32:49,134
-I've got that on a T-shirt.
-What do you mean, angels?

404
00:32:49,217 --> 00:32:53,513
-You mean those statue things?
-Creatures from another world.

405
00:32:53,722 --> 00:32:56,016
-But they're just statues.
-Only when you see them.

406
00:32:56,099 --> 00:32:57,476
What does that mean?

407
00:32:57,559 --> 00:32:59,895
The Lonely Assassins
they used to be called.

408
00:32:59,978 --> 00:33:02,772
No one quite knows where they came from,
but they're as old as the universe,

409
00:33:02,856 --> 00:33:04,858
or very nearly,
and they have survived this long

410
00:33:04,941 --> 00:33:08,028
because they have the most perfect
defence system ever evolved.

411
00:33:08,403 --> 00:33:09,696
They are quantum locked.

412
00:33:09,779 --> 00:33:11,740
They don't exist
when they're being observed.

413
00:33:11,823 --> 00:33:14,201
The moment they are seen
by any other living creature,

414
00:33:14,284 --> 00:33:15,869
they freeze into rock.

415
00:33:15,952 --> 00:33:19,498
No choice, it's a fact of their biology.
In the sight of any living thing,

416
00:33:19,581 --> 00:33:21,917
they literally turn to stone.

417
00:33:22,042 --> 00:33:24,586
And you can't kill a stone.

418
00:33:24,669 --> 00:33:28,340
Course, a stone can't kill you, either,
but then you turn your head away.

419
00:33:28,423 --> 00:33:30,050
Then you blink.

420
00:33:30,133 --> 00:33:31,968
And, oh, yes, it can.

421
00:33:32,636 --> 00:33:36,556
-Don't take your eyes off that.
-That's why they cover their eyes.

422
00:33:36,765 --> 00:33:39,434
They're not weeping,
they can't risk looking at each other.

423
00:33:39,518 --> 00:33:42,354
Their greatest asset
is their greatest curse.

424
00:33:42,437 --> 00:33:47,108
They can never be seen.
Loneliest creatures in the universe.

425
00:33:47,901 --> 00:33:52,364
Well I'm sorry. I am very, very sorry.
It's up to you now.

426
00:33:53,406 --> 00:33:56,326
-What am I supposed to do?
-The blue box. It's my time machine.

427
00:33:56,451 --> 00:33:59,371
There is a world of time energy in there
they could feast on forever,

428
00:33:59,454 --> 00:34:02,415
but the damage they could do
could switch off the sun.

429
00:34:02,499 --> 00:34:05,877
-You have got to send it back to me.
-How?

430
00:34:05,961 --> 00:34:07,462
How?

431
00:34:08,421 --> 00:34:11,466
And that's it I'm afraid.
There's no more from you

432
00:34:11,550 --> 00:34:14,511
on the transcript,
that's the last I've got.

433
00:34:14,594 --> 00:34:17,514
I don't know what stopped you talking,
but I can guess. They're coming.

434
00:34:17,639 --> 00:34:18,890
The angels are coming for you.

435
00:34:18,974 --> 00:34:21,685
But listen,
your life could depend on this.

436
00:34:21,810 --> 00:34:25,397
Don't blink. Don't even blink.
Blink and you're dead.

437
00:34:25,480 --> 00:34:27,524
They are fast.
Faster than you can believe.

438
00:34:27,607 --> 00:34:32,445
Don't turn your back,
don't look away and don't blink.

439
00:34:33,113 --> 00:34:34,990
Good luck.

440
00:34:36,825 --> 00:34:39,286
No, don't. You can't!

441
00:34:40,161 --> 00:34:42,831
-I'll rewind him.
-What good will that do?

442
00:34:44,666 --> 00:34:47,961
-You're not looking at the statue.
-Neither are you.

443
00:34:53,174 --> 00:34:55,677
Keep looking at it. Keep looking at it.

444
00:34:57,012 --> 00:34:59,222
It's just one, right?
It's just this one.

445
00:34:59,306 --> 00:35:01,850
We're okay if we just keep staring
at this one statue.

446
00:35:01,933 --> 00:35:04,060
-Everything's gonna be fine.
-There's three more.

447
00:35:04,185 --> 00:35:06,062
-Three?
-They were upstairs before,

448
00:35:06,146 --> 00:35:08,481
-but I think I heard them moving.
-Moving? Three of them?

449
00:35:08,565 --> 00:35:11,026
-Moving where?
-I'm gonna look around. I'm gonna check.

450
00:35:11,109 --> 00:35:13,403
You keep looking at this one.
Don't blink.

451
00:35:13,486 --> 00:35:15,363
Remember what he said. Don't even blink.

452
00:35:15,488 --> 00:35:17,907
Who blinked? I'm too scared to blink.

453
00:35:18,033 --> 00:35:20,785
Okay, we're going to the door.
Front door.

454
00:35:26,499 --> 00:35:28,293
Okay, we can't both get
to the front door

455
00:35:28,376 --> 00:35:30,462
without taking our eyes off that thing,
so you stay here.

456
00:35:30,545 --> 00:35:32,297
-What?
-I'll be just round the corner.

457
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:34,090
You stay here.

458
00:35:37,344 --> 00:35:39,638
They've locked it! They've locked us in.

459
00:35:39,721 --> 00:35:42,223
-Why?
-I've got something they want.

460
00:35:42,349 --> 00:35:43,933
-What?
-The key.

461
00:35:44,059 --> 00:35:46,728
I took it last time I was here.
They followed me to get it back.

462
00:35:46,811 --> 00:35:49,147
I led them to the blue box.
Now they've got that.

463
00:35:49,230 --> 00:35:51,775
Give them the key.

464
00:35:51,858 --> 00:35:54,235
I'm gonna check the back door.
You wait here.

465
00:35:54,319 --> 00:35:56,738
Give them the key!
Give them what they want!

466
00:35:58,531 --> 00:36:02,243
-Sally, no! What if they come behind me?
-Hang on!

467
00:36:02,327 --> 00:36:03,703
(DOOR RATTLING)

468
00:36:03,787 --> 00:36:04,913
God.

469
00:36:06,665 --> 00:36:09,751
-Oh, God.
-It's locked!

470
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:19,928
Sally! Sally!

471
00:36:23,098 --> 00:36:25,809
It won't open!

472
00:36:30,355 --> 00:36:32,816
Sally, please, I can't do this!

473
00:36:37,696 --> 00:36:39,948
Sally, hurry up!

474
00:36:41,574 --> 00:36:43,702
Where are you?

475
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:49,207
Larry, they've blocked up the back door,
but there's a cellar.

476
00:36:49,582 --> 00:36:52,377
There might be a way out.
Delivery hatch or something.

477
00:36:52,544 --> 00:36:55,797
I'm coming! I can't stay here.

478
00:37:16,192 --> 00:37:19,154
Okay, boys. We know how this works.

479
00:37:20,321 --> 00:37:22,991
You can't move so long as I can see you.

480
00:37:28,997 --> 00:37:31,708
A whole world in the box,
the Doctor says.

481
00:37:31,791 --> 00:37:35,295
I hope he's not lying 'cause I don't see
how else we're getting out.

482
00:37:40,049 --> 00:37:42,260
Oh, and there's your one.

483
00:37:49,267 --> 00:37:51,478
Why is it pointing at the...

484
00:37:53,021 --> 00:37:54,397
light?

485
00:37:56,024 --> 00:37:58,526
Oh, my God, it's turning out the light!

486
00:37:58,610 --> 00:38:00,820
-Quickly!
-I can't find the lock!

487
00:38:00,904 --> 00:38:02,530
Sally, hurry up!

488
00:38:04,365 --> 00:38:06,201
Get it open!

489
00:38:06,284 --> 00:38:10,163
-They're getting faster, Sally! Come on!
-It won't turn!

490
00:38:12,207 --> 00:38:14,959
-I can't turn it!
-Sally! Oh!

491
00:38:16,169 --> 00:38:18,588
Sally, hurry up! Come on!

492
00:38:33,311 --> 00:38:36,314
DOCTOR: This is Security Protocol 712.

493
00:38:36,689 --> 00:38:40,443
This time capsule has detected the
presence of an authorised control disc,

494
00:38:40,527 --> 00:38:42,445
valid one journey.

495
00:38:45,114 --> 00:38:48,409
Please insert the disc
and prepare for departure.

496
00:38:50,036 --> 00:38:52,080
Looks like a DVD player. There's a slot.

497
00:38:54,332 --> 00:38:57,252
-They're trying to get in!
-Well, hurry up, then!

498
00:39:15,103 --> 00:39:18,273
-What's happening?
-Oh, my God, it's leaving us behind.

499
00:39:18,398 --> 00:39:20,775
Doctor, don't! You can't!

500
00:39:31,953 --> 00:39:34,163
Doctor!

501
00:39:47,385 --> 00:39:49,804
Look at them! Quick, look at them!

502
00:39:53,683 --> 00:39:55,894
I don't think we need to.

503
00:39:57,729 --> 00:40:00,064
He tricked them.
The Doctor tricked them.

504
00:40:00,148 --> 00:40:03,610
They're looking at each other.
They're never gonna move again.

505
00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:34,599
Can you mind the shop? I'm just nipping
next door for some milk.

506
00:40:34,682 --> 00:40:36,309
Yeah, no worries.

507
00:40:37,685 --> 00:40:39,854
-What's this?
-Nothing.

508
00:40:50,490 --> 00:40:52,367
Sally.

509
00:40:53,743 --> 00:40:56,454
-Can't you let it go?
-Of course I can't let it go.

510
00:40:56,579 --> 00:40:57,872
This is over.

511
00:40:57,956 --> 00:41:00,458
How did the Doctor know
where to write those words on the wall?

512
00:41:00,541 --> 00:41:02,251
How could he get
a copy of the transcript?

513
00:41:02,335 --> 00:41:04,253
Where did he get
all that information from?

514
00:41:04,379 --> 00:41:08,299
Look, some things you never find out
and that's okay.

515
00:41:08,383 --> 00:41:10,009
No, it isn't.

516
00:41:14,806 --> 00:41:17,767
Ever think this might be getting
in the way of

517
00:41:19,227 --> 00:41:21,020
other things?

518
00:41:22,897 --> 00:41:25,066
We just run a shop together.

519
00:41:25,942 --> 00:41:28,403
That's all it is, just a shop.

520
00:41:29,821 --> 00:41:32,907
Anyway. Milk.

521
00:41:35,410 --> 00:41:37,120
Back in a mo.

522
00:41:52,802 --> 00:41:55,722
-Right, it's definitely this way.
-Okay.

523
00:41:58,016 --> 00:42:01,936
-Doctor! Doctor! Doctor!
-Hello. Sorry, bit of a rush.

524
00:42:02,061 --> 00:42:04,856
There's a sort of thing happening.
Very important that we stop it.

525
00:42:04,939 --> 00:42:08,234
Oh, my God, it's you. It really is you.

526
00:42:08,317 --> 00:42:10,194
Oh, you don't remember me, do you?

527
00:42:10,278 --> 00:42:12,363
Doctor, we haven't got time for this.
Migration's started.

528
00:42:12,447 --> 00:42:15,366
Look, sorry,
I've got a bit of a complex life.

529
00:42:15,450 --> 00:42:17,827
Things don't always happen to me
in quite the right order.

530
00:42:17,952 --> 00:42:20,246
Gets a bit confusing at times,
especially at weddings.

531
00:42:20,329 --> 00:42:22,707
I'm rubbish at weddings,
especially my own.

532
00:42:22,790 --> 00:42:25,543
Oh, my God, of course!
You're a time traveller.

533
00:42:25,626 --> 00:42:28,671
It hasn't happened to you yet,
none of it. It's still in your future.

534
00:42:28,755 --> 00:42:31,382
-What hasn't happened?
-Doctor, please! 20 minutes to hatching.

535
00:42:31,466 --> 00:42:35,303
It was me! Oh, for God's sake,
it was me all along.

536
00:42:35,428 --> 00:42:38,056
-You got it all from me.
-Got what?

537
00:42:38,139 --> 00:42:43,061
Okay, listen. One day,
you're gonna get stuck in 1969.

538
00:42:43,144 --> 00:42:45,813
Make sure you've got this with you.
You're gonna need it.

539
00:42:45,897 --> 00:42:48,149
-Doctor!
-Yeah! Listen, listen, gotta dash.

540
00:42:48,232 --> 00:42:52,779
Things happening. Well, four things.
Well, four things and a lizard.

541
00:42:52,862 --> 00:42:56,657
Okay, no worries. On you go.
See you around some day.

542
00:42:57,825 --> 00:43:01,120
-What was your name?
-Sally Sparrow.

543
00:43:01,204 --> 00:43:03,331
Good to meet you, Sally Sparrow.

544
00:43:15,343 --> 00:43:17,220
Goodbye, Doctor.

545
00:43:35,029 --> 00:43:36,239
Don't blink.

546
00:43:40,368 --> 00:43:41,661
Blink and you're dead.

547
00:43:44,372 --> 00:43:45,832
Don't turn your back.

548
00:43:47,792 --> 00:43:49,460
Don't look away.

549
00:43:51,003 --> 00:43:52,880
And don't blink.

550
00:43:59,387 --> 00:44:00,721
Good luck.

551
00:44:08,020 --> 00:44:09,730
We're going to the end of the universe.

552
00:44:09,814 --> 00:44:14,068
The call came from across
the stars, over and over again,

553
00:44:14,152 --> 00:44:15,444
"Come to Utopia."”

554
00:44:15,528 --> 00:44:17,238
-Doctor.
-Captain.

555
00:44:17,572 --> 00:44:19,615
(BOTH YELLING)

556
00:44:27,415 --> 00:44:28,457
It's a future time.

557
00:44:28,541 --> 00:44:29,667
Utopia is...

558
00:44:29,750 --> 00:44:33,254
The last of the humans,
scattered across the night.

559
00:44:33,337 --> 00:44:34,672
Humans are coming.

560
00:44:34,755 --> 00:44:38,259
Not even us Time Lords came this far.
We should leave.

